'''Margaret Jane Pauley''' (born October 31, 1950), better known as '''Jane Pauley''', is an [[United States|American]] television anchor and journalist, and has been involved in news reporting since 1975. She is best known for her 13-year tenure on [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today]]'' program, followed by 12 years as co-host of ''[[Dateline NBC]]'', and for her public acknowledgements of her struggle with [[bipolar disorder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abilitymagazine.com/Jane_pauley.html|title=Jane Pauley: Interview by Chet Cooper and Dr. Gillian Friedman''|publisher=Abilitymagazine.com|accessdate=2012-04-05}}</ref>

==Early life==
Pauley competed in debate and public speaking tournaments through the Indiana High School Forensic Association while enrolled at [[Warren Central High School (Indiana)|Warren Central High School]] in Indianapolis, which she graduated from in 1968.  She subsequently earned a scholarship to [[Indiana University (Bloomington)|Indiana University]], where she was involved in the [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]] sorority. After college, she worked from 1972 to 1975 at [[WISH-TV|WISH]] in Indianapolis and from 1975 to 1976 at [[WMAQ-TV|WMAQ]] in [[Chicago]] while also having a house in [[Pittsburgh]] where her sister went to work for [[Westinghouse Electric (1886)|Westinghouse]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=tstRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6m0DAAAAIBAJ&dq=today%20show%20pittsburgh&pg=6494%2C5595147|title=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette - Google News Archive Search|work=Google.com|accessdate=2015-04-30}}</ref> From there, she joined [[Television network|network television]].

==Career==
===''Today''===
From 1976 to 1989 Pauley was the co-host, with [[Tom Brokaw]] from 1976–81 and [[Bryant Gumbel]] from 1982–89, of NBC's ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]''. She also anchored the Sunday edition of ''[[NBC Nightly News]]'' from 1980-82. Following in the footsteps, both in career and in style, of the first female anchor of the show, [[Barbara Walters]], she became a symbol for professional women, more specifically, female journalists. In her autobiography, ''And So It Goes'', Pauley's colleague [[Linda Ellerbee]] wrote, "She (Pauley) is what I want to be when I grow up". NBC briefly experimented with a trio of anchors, Pauley, Gumbel, and [[Chris Wallace (journalist)|Chris Wallace]], before returning to a co-anchor format with Gumbel.{{citation needed|date = December 2013}}
[[File:Jane Pauley Tom Brokaw Today 1977.JPG|thumb|left|On the Today set with Tom Brokaw in 1977.]]
In 1989, following months of conjecture about Pauley's publicly reported dislike of the grueling morning assignment and ambition to work in prime-time television, she announced her resignation from ''Today.'' Speculation in the media seemed to imply that NBC executives had eased her out to advance younger NBC newscaster [[Deborah Norville]], who had begun to play a larger role in the two-hour morning program.

After leaving ''The Today Show'', Pauley hosted ''[[Real Life with Jane Pauley]]'' and served as deputy anchor for ''[[NBC Nightly News]]''.

In 1990, Pauley co-hosted the [[42nd Primetime Emmy Awards]], alongside [[Candice Bergen]] and [[Jay Leno]].<ref>
