===''Dateline NBC''===
From 1992 to 2003, Pauley co-hosted NBC's ''Dateline NBC''. On February 9, 1993, at the end of a regularly scheduled edition of Dateline, Pauley, along with co-host [[Stone Phillips]], delivered a public apology to [[General Motors]] on behalf of NBC. While Pauley had no connection to the story, the apology was apparently part of a settlement of a lawsuit resulting from the [[Dateline NBC#General Motors vs. NBC|now debunked 1993 report]] which aired on Dateline on November 17, 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,305709,00.html|title=Dateline Disaster|publisher=Ew.com|accessdate=2015-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatreallyhappened.com/RANCHO/LIE/nbc.html|title=Where NBC Went Wrong|publisher=Ew.com|accessdate=2015-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1993/02/10/us/nbc-settles-truck-crash-lawsuit-saying-test-was-inappropriate.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|title=NBC Settles Truck Crash Lawsuit, Saying Test Was 'Inappropriate'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2015-04-30}}</ref>

===''The Jane Pauley Show''===
{{citation needed span|text=In 2004, Pauley returned to television as host of ''[[The Jane Pauley Show]]'', a syndicated daytime talk show. On the show, she discussed her bipolar disorder at length. Much like her earlier attempt at solo hosting following her ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today]]'' tenure, ''The Jane Pauley Show'' never gained traction in the [[Nielsen ratings|ratings]] and was canceled after one season.|date=May 2015}} 

{{citation needed span|text=Since the show's cancellation, Pauley has made few appearances on television programs. She led a half-hour discussion on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]'s ''Depression: Out of the Shadows'', which aired in May 2008. She also campaigned publicly for President Obama in her home state of Indiana and participates in the Smart Talk Lecture Series.|date=May 2015}} 

{{citation needed span|text=In September 2009, Pauley lent her name to the Jane Pauley Community Health Center, a facility in collaboration between the Community Health Network and the Metropolitan School District of Warren Township, Indiana. The center serves the local community, including students and their families, regardless of insurance or income, with an emphasis on integrating medical, dental and behavioral health.|date=May 2015}} 

In 2009, Pauley joined the Board of Directors of [[The Mind Trust]], an Indianapolis-based non-profit organization that supports education innovation and reform.<ref>[http://www.themindtrust.org/about/board.aspx ]{{dead link|date=April 2015}}</ref>{{citation needed span|text=Pauley is also affiliated with the [[McGovern Institute for Brain Research]], where she serves on the institute's leadership board.  She spoke publicly about her experience with bipolar disorder at the institute’s opening ceremony in 2005, and she also appears in a 2009 video about the research mission of the institute.|date=May 2015}} {{citation needed span|text=She also serves on the board of directors and chairs the Advisory Council for the [[Children's Health Fund]] in New York City.|date=May 2015}}

===Return to ''Today''===

{{citation needed span|text=In March 2009, Jane Pauley returned to the TODAY show as a contributor on behalf of a series produced and sponsored by AARP  --  "Your Life Calling" profiling people throughout the country age 50+ who were   reinventing their lives in new and different ways. The award-winning series was on the air through 2013 and culminated in Pauley's second New York Times best-seller, "Your Life Calling:Reimagining the Rest of Your Life."|date=May 2015}}   

On December 30, 2013, Pauley, former ''Today'' co-host [[Bryant Gumbel]], current ''Today'' anchor [[Matt Lauer]] and current weather anchor [[Al Roker]] (who was live in [[Pasadena, California]]) reunited to co-host a special reunion edition of ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/30/pauley-gumbel-return-today-host-nbc-matt-lauer_n_4518458.html|title=Jane Pauley, Bryant Gumbel Return To Co-Host 'Today' (VIDEO)|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=2015-04-30}}</ref>

===CBS===
On April 27, 2014, Pauley began contributing to ''[[CBS Sunday Morning]]'' as a correspondent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jane-pauley-to-join-cbs-sunday-morning/|title=Jane Pauley to join CBS' "Sunday Morning"|date=10 April 2014|work=Cbsnews.com|accessdate=2015-04-30}}</ref> {{citation needed span|text=On August 10, 2014, Pauley guest-hosted ''CBS Sunday Morning'', and the following day began a week-long stint as a guest co-host on ''[[CBS This Morning]]'', substituting for [[Gayle King]].|date=May 2015}} {{citation needed span|text= On March 15, 2015, Pauley again guest-hosted ''CBS Sunday Morning''.|date=May 2015}}

==Accolades==
* 1998: [[Paul White (journalist)|Paul White]] Award, [[Radio Television Digital News Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtdna.org/content/paul_white_award#.U4FBHS8-Ngc |title=Paul White Award |publisher=[[Radio Television Digital News Association]] |accessdate=2014-05-27}}</ref>

==Personal life==
The timing of her announcement that she is diagnosed with bipolar disorder coincided with the release of her autobiography, ''Skywriting: A Life Out of the Blue'' (2004) and the launch of her daytime talk show.<ref>{{cite news| author =| title =Jane Pauley shares her story| quote =Most at NBC didn't know about her illness or that during a leave from the network, she'd been admitted to a psychiatric clinic.| newspaper =[[NBC News]]| date = September 4, 2004| url =http://www.nbcnews.com/id/5887567/ns/dateline_nbc-books/t/jane-pauley-shares-her-story/#.VVbl9mYnhPQ| accessdate =May 16, 2015}}</ref>

In October 2006, Pauley and her lawyers filed a lawsuit against ''[[The New York Times]]'' for allegedly duping her into lending her name and likeness to an advertising supplement popular with drug companies. Pauley maintains she believed she was being interviewed by a ''Times'' reporter.<ref>{{cite news| author =| title = Jane Pauley Sues New York Times Over Ad Supplement| quote =| newspaper =[[Associated Press]] via [[The New York Times]]| date =October 26, 2006| url =http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/26/business/media/26times.html| accessdate =May 16, 2015}}</ref>

Pauley is married to the cartoonist [[Garry Trudeau]], author of ''[[Doonesbury]]'', and they have three children.<ref>{{cite news| author =Jane Hall| title =Fighting Off a Few Guilty Tears, Jane Pauley Leaves Her Kids at Home and Heads Back to Work on Today| quote =| newspaper =People| date =October 27, 1986| url =http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20094866,00.html| accessdate =May 16, 2015}}</ref>

